{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474094"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:17:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:17:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11780"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11780"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.01,0.92,0.01,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4392"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112669"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4392"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11780"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94702"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1643"},{"type":"tags","id":"2290"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4951"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"5426"},{"type":"tags","id":"9623"},{"type":"tags","id":"11572"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9468"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9600"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42663"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44108"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46229"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112669"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-month-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother for his six-month immunisations and check-up. It is his first time at this clinic and there is no record of his medical history apart from the blue book brought by his mother. She does not have any concerns regarding her son\u0027s development. He was born at 38 weeks via vaginal delivery and weighed 3.2 kg. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears slightly underweight with height and weight at the 35th and 25th percentiles respectively, down from the 50th and 45th percentiles at four months. Prior to this visit his height and weight had been consistent since birth. He has delayed milestones. Rashes are noted in the groin and buttock region. A bruise is seen over his left gluteus, which the mother reports occurred when he fell over while walking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurther questioning reveals that the child has been irritable and feeding poorly for the past two weeks. The mother also mentions that he has had several episodes of vomiting and diarrhoea. There are no signs of dehydration. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important differential diagnosis to consider?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Coeliac disease","Bleeding disorder","Child abuse","Inborn error of metabolism","Congenital hypothyroidism"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAll the options could cause a decline in the child\u0027s growth, however the most concerning is that he has signs that are suspicious of \u003Cstrong\u003Echild abuse\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a decline in both his height and weight percentiles, suggesting a nutritional or gastrointestinal cause. The most common causes of failure to thrive are non-organic causes such as inappropriate feeding practices or feed sizes, child neglect, intrauterine growth restriction or prematurity/ low birth weight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to the physical examination findings, the most worrisome cause is abuse and neglect. The bruising pattern is concerning for physical abuse. Firstly, children generally begin to walk around 12 months, so the mother\u0027s story is inconsistent with expected developmental milestones. Secondly, the bruising lies across soft tissue, while accidental bruises generally occur over bony prominences.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFeatures of bruising concerning for child abuse include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epattern of bruising not consistent with method of injury\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Echild\u0027s developmental age not consistent with injury\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Esignificant injury with little explanation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Erecurrent injuries\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ebruises over cheeks, ears, neck, trunk and arms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERed flags for neglect and abuse:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Elack of appropriate socialisation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Echronic diaper rash\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eimpetigo\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eflat occiput\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epoor hygiene\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ebruises and scars inconsistent with the parents\u0027 reported mechanism of injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoeliac disease\u003C/strong\u003E results in malabsorption, which can present with failure to thrive. However, it usually presents after introduction of wheat-containing weaning foods, and also with symptoms such as abdominal distension and gluteal muscle wasting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBleeding disorders\u003C/strong\u003E such as haemophilia, thrombocytopenia and von Willebrand disease should be considered in children with abnormal bruising. However, there is insufficient evidence of abnormal bruising, as the patient presented with only a single bruise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInborn errors of metabolism\u003C/strong\u003E are rare inherited disorders usually caused by defects in specific enzymes that metabolize parts of food. Several cause developmental delays or other medical problems if uncontrolled. Common types include fructose intolerance, galactosaemia, maple syrup urine disease, and phenylketonuria. Patients with severe errors in metabolism typically present early and catastrophically in the neonatal period, making this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with \u003Cstrong\u003Econgenital hypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E are usually asymptomatic at birth, or may present with subtle clinical features like prolonged neonatal jaundice, constipation, lethargy and being a quiet baby. If left untreated, overt clinical signs appear at 3-6 months, such as lack of weight gain, stunted growth, hypotonia, delayed milestones and umbilical hernia. There aren\u0027t many suggestive features in the stem, but it should still be considered in the differential for this previously well child with sudden growth deterioration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bruises inconsistent with a child\u0027s developmental milestones increase suspicion for child abuse.","Differential diagnosis of a child with failure to thrive includes non-organic causes, coeliac disease, inborn errors of metabolism, and congenital hypothyroidism."],"references":["Chapple D. More than just a bruise: Recognizing child physical abuse. BC Medical Journal. 2015;57(7):288-292.","Child Protection - TeachMePaediatrics - Emotional - Physical - Sexual [Internet]. TeachMePaediatrics. 2022 [cited 15 May 2022]. Available from: https://teachmepaediatrics.com/community/holistic-care/child-protection/","Bergman P, Graham J. An approach to \u2018failure to thrive\u2019. Australian Family Physician. 2005;34(9):725-729."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94702"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11780"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94702"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-03T10:39:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-03T10:42:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4392"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112669"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"d